
I have a sizeable VT position in my taxable account. (While not very relevant here, all my other accounts are 100% VEQT).

I want to add VCN to the taxable account because I''d like to add in some home country bias to smooth out currency volatility and increase tax efficiency:

- I don''t want to sell VT (thus triggering large cap gains) just to switch over to VEQT.
- So, I would just buy VCN now onwards until the Canadian portion of the account (i.e. VCN + 2% Canada in VT) become about ~25%.
- This way, I get the Canadian dividend tax credit benefit which VEQT provides (through VCN in this case).
- Since VCN and VT both have a MER of 0.06%, I don''t increase spend on fees either.
- Once ~25% is attained, then buy VEQT (plus any VCN/VT rebalances using new money as needed to maintain the ratio)

Now, I am aware that while this fixes the home country bias challenge, it won''t do away with US Estate Tax related filings when the time comes. 

