currency exposure, and desired asset allocation while maintaining low-cost investment strategies.', '{"original_title" : "Adding VCN to VT in taxable account for VEQT-like attributes.", "original_body" : "So, just wanted some feedback/opinions on my line of thinking/plan.\n\nI have a sizeable VT position in my taxable account. (While not very relevant here, all my other accounts are 100% VEQT).\n\nI want to add VCN to the taxable account because I''d like to add in some home country bias to smooth out currency volatility and increase tax efficiency:\n\n- I don''t want to sell VT (thus triggering large cap gains) just to switch over to VEQT.\n- So, I would just buy VCN now onwards until the Canadian portion of the account (i.e. VCN + 2% Canada in VT) become about ~25%.\n- This way, I get the Canadian dividend tax credit benefit which VEQT provides (through VCN in this case).\n- Since VCN and VT both have a MER of 0.06%, I don''t increase spend on fees either.\n- Once ~25% is attained, then buy VEQT (plus any VCN/VT rebalances using new money as needed to maintain the ratio)\n\nNow, I am aware that while this fixes the home country bias challenge, it won''t do away with US Estate Tax related filings when the time comes. \n\nHonestly, I wish there was a way to replace VT with VEQT without a huge tax bill, but aside from Estate Taxes, the \"add VCN\" approach seems like the optimal way to get close to VEQT-like attributes (with an unintended bonus of a 0.06% MER). Thoughts?", "subreddit" : "r/technology_and_software", "upvotes" : 1, "comments" : 1, "platform" : "reddit", "url" : "", "confidence_score" : 0.85}', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL) ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO opportunities (id, title, description, category, subcategory, severity, validation_count, growth_rate, market_size, geographic_scope, country, region, city, completion_status, solution_description, solved_at, solved_by, feasibility_score, duplicate_of, author_id, is_anonymous, status, created_at, updated_at, source_id, source_url, source_platform, ai_analyzed, ai_analyzed_at, ai_opportunity_score, ai_summary, ai_market_size_estimate, ai_competition_level, ai_urgency_level, ai_target_audience, ai_pain_intensity, ai_business_model_suggestions, ai_competitive_advantages, ai_key_risks, ai_next_steps, ai_generated_title, ai_problem_statement, raw_source_data, latitude, longitude, demographics, search_trends, demographics_fetched_at) VALUES (93, 'miniFL - A Team-Builder''s Paradise', 'Most Madden leagues are built for people who want constant user games, meta playbooks, and rigid rules that kill creativity.



If you’re the type who:

* enjoys **building a roster over seasons**
* likes experimenting with positions and player roles
* actually cares about progression, cap decisions, and long-term team identity
* gets bored playing the same “correct” way every league



…then you’re probably in the wrong leagues.



**miniFL** is an 8-user, adult sim league built around the *team-building loop*.

Light rules. Honor system. Freedom to build your team your way — in exchange for balanced, non-lobby gameplay (no Bunch/Tight spam).



We’re in **Season 5**, and the league has developed real continuity — teams, storylines, and reputations that carry over year to year.



# Quick facts

* PS5 • Madden 26 • Crossplay
* 8 users (1 per division)
* 24h advances (48h for scheduled UvU)
* All-Pro • Sim • 6-minute quarters (\~45 min games)
* **Bunch & Tights banned**
* Custom playbooks allowed
* Stock sliders • Practice injuries OFF • Wear & Tear OFF
